---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Compare', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Ultra Zoom vs. Hover Zoom', item: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare/hover-zoom' },
  ],
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is Hover Zoom still safe to use?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The original Hover Zoom was caught logging the URLs of every page its users visited and selling that browsing data. Even after the ownership change, many security write-ups still recommend uninstalling it. Ultra Zoom keeps the same hover-to-zoom workflow without any analytics, telemetry, or remote code.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is Ultra Zoom a Hover Zoom replacement?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes. Ultra Zoom matches the core Hover Zoom workflow — instant hover preview on image-heavy sites, gallery navigation, full-resolution previews — and adds active development, native Manifest V3 builds, on-device AI upscaling, and zero telemetry.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How is Ultra Zoom different from Hover Zoom?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Ultra Zoom has no analytics endpoint, no remote code, and no server that sees your browsing — by design, not by promise. It ships releases every few weeks, supports current Manifest V3 in Chrome, Edge and Brave, and has a native Firefox add-on.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Ultra Zoom vs. Hover Zoom — A Privacy-First Hover Zoom Alternative"
  description="Hover Zoom was caught selling browsing data. Ultra Zoom is the modern, privacy-first hover-to-zoom extension for Chrome and Firefox with the workflow you already know."
  currentPage="compare"
  og={{
    url: 'https://ultrazoom.app/compare/hover-zoom',
    title: 'Ultra Zoom vs. Hover Zoom',
    description: 'A privacy-first, actively maintained Hover Zoom alternative for Chrome and Firefox.',
    image: 'https://ultrazoom.app/og/compare-hover-zoom.png',
    imageWidth: 1200,
    imageHeight: 630,
  }}
  jsonLd={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema]}
>
    <main class="main page-content" id="main-content">
        <h1>Ultra Zoom vs. Hover Zoom</h1>

        <p class="pricing-intro">Hover Zoom was the extension that made hover-to-zoom mainstream &mdash; and then <a href="/blog/hover-zoom-privacy-scandal">got caught selling its users&rsquo; browsing data</a>. Even years later, the trust isn&rsquo;t back. Ultra Zoom keeps the muscle memory you already have and pairs it with a privacy story Hover Zoom can&rsquo;t match.</p>

        <section class="help-section" id="why-switch">
            <h2>Why people are switching</h2>
            <ul class="help-list">
                <li><strong>Zero telemetry by design.</strong> No analytics endpoint, no remote code, no server that sees your browsing. <a href="/blog/zero-knowledge-architecture">Read the architecture</a>.</li>
                <li><strong>Active development.</strong> New site plugins and bug fixes ship every few weeks &mdash; not on whatever schedule a long-since-sold extension feels like.</li>
                <li><strong>Manifest V3 native.</strong> Built for the current Chrome extension platform <a href="/blog/manifest-v3-trap">without the V3 trap</a> that breaks legacy hover-zoom extensions.</li>
                <li><strong>Real Pro tier.</strong> Power features (AI upscaling, video controls, advanced gallery, hover history search) ship under a transparent Stripe-managed plan with a 7-day free trial.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="feature-parity">
            <h2>Feature parity at a glance</h2>
            <div class="pricing-compare-wrap">
                <table class="pricing-compare">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="col">Feature</th>
                            <th scope="col">Hover Zoom</th>
                            <th scope="col">Ultra Zoom</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Hover-to-zoom on every site</th>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Site-specific plugins (Instagram, Amazon, etc.)</th>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Caught logging browsing data</th>
                            <td aria-label="Yes">Yes (2013)</td>
                            <td aria-label="No">Never</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Theater mode (Z)</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Reverse image search shortcuts</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">On-device AI upscaling (Real-ESRGAN)</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003; (Pro)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Video preview &amp; playback controls</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003; (Pro)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Hover history</th>
                            <td aria-label="Not included">&ndash;</td>
                            <td>50 free / 1,000 + search (Pro)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Manifest V3 native</th>
                            <td aria-label="Partial">Partial</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Active release cadence</th>
                            <td aria-label="Limited">Limited</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">Every few weeks</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">Zero telemetry guarantee</th>
                            <td aria-label="No">No</td>
                            <td aria-label="Included">&#10003;</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="privacy">
            <h2>The Hover Zoom privacy story, in short</h2>
            <p>In 2013, security researchers caught Hover Zoom logging the URL of every page its users visited and selling that browsing data to a third-party broker. The extension stayed up. Ownership changed. The community forked, then forked again. The current Chrome Web Store listing carries a permission warning. Many users who installed it years ago still have it sitting silently in their toolbar &mdash; this is your reminder to check.</p>
            <p>If you&rsquo;d rather not audit a black box, Ultra Zoom&rsquo;s zero-knowledge architecture means there&rsquo;s nothing to audit: no endpoint, no telemetry, no remote loader.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="migration">
            <h2>Coming over from Hover Zoom</h2>
            <ul class="help-list">
                <li>Install Ultra Zoom and disable (or uninstall) Hover Zoom &mdash; running both will conflict on the hover overlay.</li>
                <li>Open the popup. The default site catalogue covers everything Hover Zoom did, plus newer sources like Unsplash, Pexels, Wikimedia, Bilibili, and Avito.</li>
                <li>If you used Hover Zoom&rsquo;s blacklist, Ultra Zoom&rsquo;s per-site toggle is one click away in the toolbar popup.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="cta">
            <h2>Try it free</h2>
            <p>The core extension is free forever, with the entire site catalogue. Pro is a 7-day free trial when you&rsquo;re ready &mdash; <a href="/pricing">see plans</a>.</p>
            <ul class="install-links">
                <li>
                    <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/ultra-zoom/jalclpdejbeamaamcpbolkclpnleagmg" class="install-button chrome" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Install for Chrome</a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/ultra-zoom/" class="install-button firefox" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Install for Firefox</a>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
    </main>
</BaseLayout>
